Headquarters Regions: Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: EscaWheel is a patent-pending wheelchair accessibility device that takes wheelchairs up and down stairs in a way that is more efficient and cost-effective than the currently existing technology. Where stairlifts and platform lifts fail, EscaWheel excels by lifting the wheelchair in a new way. This allows EscaWheel to take wheelchair users up and down stairs at a low cost without sacrificing functionality. The two current options for wheelchair users to use stairs in their home are vastly inadequate. Stairlifts require the user to get out of their wheelchair, into the stairlift and then into another wheelchair at the top of the stairs. This almost always required an attendant, especially for the ill or elderly. Platform lifts are easier to use, however they designed for institutional settings and require staircases that are much wider than a residential staircase. They are also prohibitively expensive and can be upwards of $20,000 installed.

Full Description: Value-added seed and angel capital, with experienced advice at key inflection points: positioning, raising capital, connections, team building, bus dev, sales, messaging, marketing, communications, M&A / IPO.  WHAT WE LOOK FOR -  Significant market potential. High conviction, high commitment founders. Core teammates who have proven they can execute. Well-differentiated solutions with obvious appeal. Competitive advantage.  Solid plan.  Good chemistry. PORTFOLIO -  Theorem portfolio companies include Delphix, Smule, Automatic, FundersClub, Visual.ly, Unified Social, Sokanu, Pixt, Trustpipe, Traackr, Chirpify, Raise.me, OfferUp and 915Labs.  Exits include MP3.com, Sigaba, Atomic, ComContext, H30, Zui & Moonfruit.  Pagelever was acquired in 2013 for shares in Unified Social. GEOGRAPHICS -  Theorem is focused on companies based in San Francisco & Silicon Valley. HISTORY -  Theorem partners Andy Getsey and James Hannon started with an investment in the IPO of MP3.com, and have made 20 select investments with 7 exits to date.   MORE BACKGROUND -  Andy and James are entrepreneurs and angel investors who understand first hand what it takes to launch and commercialize technologies and tech-related companies. Together, they co-developed a pioneering analytics platform, launched two companies and created an international joint venture with a publicly traded company – all of which were acquired. Along the way, they negotiated more than 500 contracts, opened 7 office locations and managed more than 200 staff in the US and Europe. In addition, they’ve invested in more than 20 companies, with 6 acquisitions and one IPO to date. They were the co-founders of Atomic, which became one of the fastest growing SF Bay Area companies for 5 years running, and one of Silicon Valley's premiere PR and social agencies for startups.
